<subSubSection pageNumber="282" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageNumber="282">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="282">Note:</emphasis>
In the protologue, Linnaeus referred to 
<normalizedToken originalValue="“Alyssum”">&quot;Alyssum&quot;</normalizedToken>
from &quot;Ard. Spec. 2. p. t. 10&quot;. No page number was given, but t. 10 in 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="282">Animadv. Bot. Spec. Alt.</emphasis>
(1764) is an 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="282">
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Caryophyllaceae" genus="Arenaria" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Plantae" order="Caryophyllales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">Arenaria</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Linnaeus’">Linnaeus'</normalizedToken>
diagnosis is a close match for the text on p. 30, and the illustration at t. 14, both associated with 
<taxonomicName class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Alyssum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="petraeum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="282">Alyssum petraeum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Ard., a valid binomial. Ball &amp; Dudley (in Turin &amp; al., 
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="282">Fl. Europaea</emphasis>
1: 299. 1964) have treated the two names as synonymous, and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Linnaeus" authorityYear="1767" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Brassicaceae" genus="Alyssum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Brassicales" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="gemonense">
<emphasis italics="true" pageNumber="282">A. gemonense</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
appears to be illegitimate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
